        img(src="images/shape/sw19.jpg")

      section.emphatic-text(data-bespoke-backdrop='emphatic')
        h3 To change shadow effects:
        li Adding a shadow to a shape can make it appear as though it is floating above the page, and it can help to add contrast between the shape and the background.
        li Select the shape or text box you want to change.

      section.emphatic-text(data-bespoke-backdrop='emphatic')
        li On the Format tab, click the Shape Effects drop-down arrow. In the menu that appears, hover the mouse over Shadow and select the shadow you want to use.
        img(src="images/shape/sw20.jpg")
        li The shape will appear with the selected shadow.

      section.emphatic-text(data-bespoke-backdrop='emphatic')
        li To adjust the shadow color, size, and distance, select Shadow Options from the drop-down menu. The Format Shape pane will appear on the right side of the PowerPoint window, allowing you to customize the shadow.
        img(src="images/shape/sw21.jpg")

      section.emphatic-text(data-bespoke-backdrop='emphatic')
        h2 3D effects
        li There are two kinds of effects you can apply to your shapes and text boxes to give them a 3D appearance: Bevel and 3-D Rotation. Bevel adds thickness and a rounded edge to shapes, but it doesn't work with every type of shape. 3-D Rotation gives the appearance that you are viewing the object from a different angle, and it can be applied to any shape.

      section.emphatic-text(data-bespoke-backdrop='emphatic')
        h3 To add a bevel:
        li Select the shape or text box you want to change.

      section.emphatic-text(data-bespoke-backdrop='emphatic')
        li On the Format tab, click the Shape Effects drop-down arrow. In the menu that appears, hover the mouse over Bevel and select the desired bevel preset.
        img(src="images/shape/sw22.jpg")

      section.emphatic-text(data-bespoke-backdrop='emphatic')
        li The shape will appear in the selected bevel effect.
        img(src="images/shape/sw23.jpg")

      section.emphatic-text(data-bespoke-backdrop='emphatic')
        li If desired, you can customize the bevel effect. Select 3-D Options from the drop-down menu. The Format Shape pane will appear on the right side of the PowerPoint window. From here, you can modify the width, height, and depth of a bevel. 
        img(src="images/shape/sw24.jpg")

      section.emphatic-text(data-bespoke-backdrop='emphatic')
        h3 To add 3-D Rotation:
        li Select the shape or text box you want to change.

      section.emphatic-text(data-bespoke-backdrop='emphatic')
        li On the Format tab, click the Shape Effects drop-down arrow. In the menu that appears, hover the mouse over 3-D Rotation and select the desired 3D effect.
        img(src="images/shape/sw25.jpg")

      section.emphatic-text(data-bespoke-backdrop='emphatic')
        li If desired, you can customize 3-D Rotation. Select 3-D Rotation Options from the drop-down menu, and the Format Shape panel will appear on the right side of the PowerPoint window.
        img(src="images/shape/sw26.jpg")

      section.emphatic-text(data-bespoke-backdrop='emphatic')
         h2 Arranging Objects
         h3 Aligning objects
         p When you move objects in PowerPoint, alignment guides and spacing guides will appear around the objects to help you align them. However, if you have many different objects on a slide, it may be difficult and time consuming to get them perfectly aligned. Luckily, PowerPoint provides you with several alignment commands that allow you to easily arrange and position objects.

       section.emphatic-text(data-bespoke-backdrop='emphatic')
          img(src="images/arrange/arrange_align_lines3.png")

       section.emphatic-text(data-bespoke-backdrop='emphatic')
         h3 To align two or more objects:
         li Click and drag your mouse to form a selection box around the objects you want to align. The Format tab will appear.
         img(src="images/arrange/arrange_select_obj2.jpeg")

       section.emphatic-text(data-bespoke-backdrop='emphatic')
          li From the Format tab, click the Align command, then select Align Selected Objects.

       section.emphatic-text(data-bespoke-backdrop='emphatic')
          img(src="images/arrange/arrange_align_comm_alignob2.jpeg")

       section.emphatic-text(data-bespoke-backdrop='emphatic')
          li Click the Align command again, then select one of the six alignment options.

       section.emphatic-text(data-bespoke-backdrop='emphatic')
          img(src="images/arrange/arrange_align_comm_alignmd4.jpeg")

       section.emphatic-text(data-bespoke-backdrop='emphatic')
          li The objects will align based on the option you selected.
          img(src="images/arrange/arrange_align_mid_after2.jpeg")

        section.emphatic-text(data-bespoke-backdrop='emphatic')
           h3 To align objects to the slide:
           p ometimes you may wish to align one or more objects to a specific location within the slide, such as at the top or bottom. You can do this by simply selecting the Align to Slide option before you align the objects.
           li Click and drag your mouse to form a selection box around the objects you want to align.
           li From the Format tab, click the Align command, then select Align to Slide.

         section.emphatic-text(data-bespoke-backdrop='emphatic')
            img(src="images/arrange/arrange_align_comm_alignsl2.jpeg")

         section.emphatic-text(data-bespoke-backdrop='emphatic')
            li Click the Align command again, then select one of the six alignment options

         section.emphatic-text(data-bespoke-backdrop='emphatic')
            img(src="images/arrange/arrange_align_comm_algnbt4.jpeg")

         section.emphatic-text(data-bespoke-backdrop='emphatic')
           li The objects will align based on the option you selected.
           img(src="images/arrange/arrange_align_bot_after2.jpeg")

         section.emphatic-text(data-bespoke-backdrop='emphatic')
           h3 To distribute objects evenly:
           p If you have arranged objects in a row or column, you may want them to be an equal distance from one another for a neater appearance. You can do this by distributing the objects horizontally or vertically.
           li Click and drag your mouse to form a selection box around the objects you want to align.
           li From the Format tab, click the Align command, then select Align to Slide or Align Selected Objects.

         section.emphatic-text(data-bespoke-backdrop='emphatic')
           img(src="images/arrange/arrange_align_comm_alignob2.jpeg")

         section.emphatic-text(data-bespoke-backdrop='emphatic')
           li Click the Align command again, then select Distribute Horizontally or Distribute Vertically from the drop-down menu that appears.

         section.emphatic-text(data-bespoke-backdrop='emphatic')
           img(src="images/arrange/arrange_align_comm_horiz4.jpeg")

         section.emphatic-text(data-bespoke-backdrop='emphatic')
           li The objects will distribute evenly.
           img(src="images/arrange/arrange_align_horiz_after3.jpeg")

         section.emphatic-text(data-bespoke-backdrop='emphatic')
           h2 Ordering objects
           p In addition to aligning objects, PowerPoint gives you the ability to arrange objects in a specific order. The ordering is important when two or more objects overlap, as it will determine which objects are in the front or the back.
           
         section.emphatic-text(data-bespoke-backdrop='emphatic')
           h3 Understanding levels
           p When objects are inserted into a slide, they are placed on levels according to the order in which they were inserted into the slide. In the image below, the rectangle is on the top level, but we can change the level to put it behind the other objects.

         section.emphatic-text(data-bespoke-backdrop='emphatic')
            img(src="images/arrange/arrange_select_shape2.jpeg")

         section.emphatic-text(data-bespoke-backdrop='emphatic')
            h2 To change the ordering by one level:
            li Select an object. The Format tab will appear.

         section.emphatic-text(data-bespoke-backdrop='emphatic')
            img(src="images/arrange/arrange_select_shape2.jpeg")

         section.emphatic-text(data-bespoke-backdrop='emphatic')
            li From the Format tab, click the Bring Forward or Send Backward command to change the object's ordering by one level. If there are multiple objects on the slide, you may need to click the command several times to achieve the desired ordering.

         section.emphatic-text(data-bespoke-backdrop='emphatic')
            img(src="images/arrange/arrange_backward_comm.jpeg")

         section.emphatic-text(data-bespoke-backdrop='emphatic')
            li The objects will reorder.
            img(src="images/arrange/arrange_backward_after2.jpeg")

         section.emphatic-text(data-bespoke-backdrop='emphatic')
            h3 To bring an object to the front or back:
            p If you want to move an object behind or in front of several objects, it's usually faster to bring it to front or send it to back rather than clicking the ordering commands multiple times.

         section.emphatic-text(data-bespoke-backdrop='emphatic')
           li Select an object.
           li From the Format tab, click the Bring Forward or Send Backward drop-down box
           li From the drop-down menu, select Bring to Front or Send to Back.

         section.emphatic-text(data-bespoke-backdrop='emphatic')
            img(src="images/arrange/arrange_backward_back.jpeg")

         section.emphatic-text(data-bespoke-backdrop='emphatic')
            li The objects will reorder.
            img(src="images/arrange/arrange_backward_back_aftr3.jpeg")

         section.emphatic-text(data-bespoke-backdrop='emphatic')
            h2 Rotating objects
            p If you need to turn an object so it faces a different direction, you can rotate it to the left or right or flip it horizontally or vertically.

         section.emphatic-text(data-bespoke-backdrop='emphatic')
            h3 To rotate an object:
            li Select an object. The Format tab will appear.
            li From the Format tab, click the Rotate command. A drop-down menu will appear.
            li Select the desired rotation option.

         section.emphatic-text(data-bespoke-backdrop='emphatic')
            img(src="images/arrange/arrange_rotate_comm.jpeg")

         section.emphatic-text(data-bespoke-backdrop='emphatic')
            li The object will rotate.
            img(src="images/arrange/arrange_rotate_after2.jpeg")

         section.emphatic-text(data-bespoke-backdrop='emphatic')
            h2 Grouping objects
            p You may want to group multiple objects into one object so they will stay together if they are moved or resized. This is often easier than selecting all of the objects every time you want to move them.
            p Pictures, shapes, clip art, and text boxes can all be grouped together; however, placeholders cannot be grouped. If you will be grouping pictures, use one of the commands in the Images group on the Insert tab to insert pictures instead of the picture icon inside the placeholder.

         section.emphatic-text(data-bespoke-backdrop='emphatic')
           img(src="images/arrange/arange_insert_images.jpeg")

         section.emphatic-text(data-bespoke-backdrop='emphatic')
            h3 To group objects:
            li Click and drag your mouse to form a selection box around the objects you want to group. The Format tab will appear.

         section.emphatic-text(data-bespoke-backdrop='emphatic')
            img(src="images/arrange/arrange_group_select_obj2.jpeg")

         section.emphatic-text(data-bespoke-backdrop='emphatic')
            li From the Format tab, click the Group command, then select Group.
            img(src="images/arrange/arrange_group_comm2.jpeg")

         section.emphatic-text(data-bespoke-backdrop='emphatic')
            li The selected objects will now be grouped. There will be a single box with sizing handles around the entire group to show that they are one group. You can now move or resize all of the objects at once.

         section.emphatic-text(data-bespoke-backdrop='emphatic')
            img(src="images/arrange/arrange_group_after2.jpeg")

         section.emphatic-text(data-bespoke-backdrop='emphatic')
            h3 To ungroup objects:
            li Select the grouped object you wish to ungroup.
            li From the Format tab, click the Group command, then select Ungroup.

         section.emphatic-text(data-bespoke-backdrop='emphatic')
            img(src="images/arrange/arrange_ungroup_comm.jpeg")

         section.emphatic-text(data-bespoke-backdrop='emphatic')
            li The objects will be ungrouped.
            img(src="images/arrange/arrange_ungroup_after2.jpeg")

         section.emphatic-text(data-bespoke-backdrop='emphatic')
            h2 Animating Text and Objects
            p In PowerPoint, you can animate text and objects such as clip art, shapes, and pictures. Animation—or movement—on the slide can be used to draw the audience's attention to specific content or to make the slide easier to read.

         section.emphatic-text(data-bespoke-backdrop='emphatic')
            h3 The four types of animations :
            li Entrance: These control how the object enters the slide. For example, with the Bounce animation the object will "fall" onto the slide and then bounce several times.
            img(src="images/animation/effect2.jpeg")

         section.emphatic-text(data-bespoke-backdrop='emphatic')
            li Emphasis: These animations occur while the object is on the slide, often triggered by a mouse click. For example, you can set an object to Spin when you click the mouse.
            img(src="images/animation/effect1.jpeg")

         section.emphatic-text(data-bespoke-backdrop='emphatic')
            li Exit: These control how the object exits the slide. For example, with the Fade animation the object will simply fade away.
            img(src="images/animation/effect3.jpeg")
 
         section.emphatic-text(data-bespoke-backdrop='emphatic')
            li Motion Paths: These are similar to Emphasis effects, except that the object moves within the slide along a predetermined path, like a circle.
            img(src="images/animation/paths.png")

         section.emphatic-text(data-bespoke-backdrop='emphatic')
            h3 To apply an animation to an object:
            li Select the object you want to animate.

         section.emphatic-text(data-bespoke-backdrop='emphatic')
            li On the Animations tab, click the More drop-down arrow in the Animation group.
            img(src="images/animation/click.jpeg")

         section.emphatic-text(data-bespoke-backdrop='emphatic')
            li A drop-down menu of animation effects will appear. Select the desired effect.
            img(src="images/animation/flyin_effect.jpeg")

         section.emphatic-text(data-bespoke-backdrop='emphatic')
            li The effect will apply to the object. The object will have a small number next to it to show that it has an animation. In the Slide pane, a star symbol also will appear next to the slide.
            img(src="images/animation/indicators.jpeg")

         section.emphatic-text(data-bespoke-backdrop='emphatic')
            h3 Effect options
            p Some effects will have options you can change. For example, with the Fly In effect you can control which direction the object comes from. These options can be accessed from the Effect Options command in the Animation group.
            img(src="images/animation/options.jpeg")

         section.emphatic-text(data-bespoke-backdrop='emphatic')
            h3 To remove an animation

         section.emphatic-text(data-bespoke-backdrop='emphatic')
            li Select the small number located next to the animated object.
            img(src="images/animation/animation.jpeg")

            li Press the Delete key. The animation will be deleted.

         section.emphatic-text(data-bespoke-backdrop='emphatic')
            h3 To add multiple animations to an object:
            p If you select a new animation from the the menu in the Animation group, it will replace the object's current animation. However, you'll sometimes want to place more than one animation on an object, like an Entrance and an Exit effect. To do this, you'll need to use the Add Animation command, which will allow you to keep your current animations while adding new ones.
      
         section.emphatic-text(data-bespoke-backdrop='emphatic')
            li Select an object.
            li Click the Animations tab.
            li In the Advanced Animation group, click the Add Animation command to view the available animations.

         section.emphatic-text(data-bespoke-backdrop='emphatic')
            li Select the desired animation effect.
            img(src="images/animation/animation1.jpeg")

         section.emphatic-text(data-bespoke-backdrop='emphatic')
            li If the object has more than one effect, it will have a different number for each effect. The numbers indicate the order in which the effects will occur.
            img(src="images/animation/indicators1.jpeg")

         section.emphatic-text(data-bespoke-backdrop='emphatic')
            h3 To preview animations:
            p Any animation effects you have applied will show up when you play the slide show. However, you can also quickly preview the animations for the current slide without viewing the slide show.

         section.emphatic-text(data-bespoke-backdrop='emphatic')
            li Navigate to the slide you want to preview.
            li From the Animations tab, click the Preview command. The animations for the current slide will play.
            img(src="images/animation/comm.jpeg")

         section.emphatic-text(data-bespoke-backdrop='emphatic')
            h2 The Animation Pane
            p The Animation Pane allows you to view and manage all of the effects that are on the current slide. You can modify and reorder effects directly from the Animation Pane, which is especially useful when you have several effects.

         section.emphatic-text(data-bespoke-backdrop='emphatic')
            h3 To open the Animation Pane:
       
         section.emphatic-text(data-bespoke-backdrop='emphatic')
            li From the Animations tab, click the Animation Pane command.
            img(src="images/animation/comm1.jpeg")

         section.emphatic-text(data-bespoke-backdrop='emphatic')
            li The Animation Pane will open on the right side of the window. It will show all of the effects for the current slide in the order in which they will appear.
            img(src="images/animation/pane.jpeg")

         section.emphatic-text(data-bespoke-backdrop='emphatic')
            h3 To reorder effects from the Animation Pane:
 
         section.emphatic-text(data-bespoke-backdrop='emphatic')
            li On the Animation Pane, click and drag an effect up or down.
            img(src="images/animation/reor.jpeg")

            li The effects will reorder themselves.

         section.emphatic-text(data-bespoke-backdrop='emphatic')
            h3 To preview effects from the Animation Pane:

         section.emphatic-text(data-bespoke-backdrop='emphatic')
            li From the Animation Pane, click the Play button.
            img(src="images/animation/play.jpeg")

         section.emphatic-text(data-bespoke-backdrop='emphatic')
            li The effects for the current slide will play. On the right side of the Animation Pane, you will be able to see a timeline that shows the progress through each effect.
            img(src="images/animation/time.jpeg")

         section.emphatic-text(data-bespoke-backdrop='emphatic')
            h2 The Effect Options dialog box
            p From the Animation Pane, you can access the Effect Options dialog box, which contains more advanced options you can use to fine tune your animations.

         section.emphatic-text(data-bespoke-backdrop='emphatic')
            h3 To change the effect timing:
            
         section.emphatic-text(data-bespoke-backdrop='emphatic')
            li From the Effect Options dialog box, select the Timing tab.
            img(src="images/animation/timing.png")

         section.emphatic-text(data-bespoke-backdrop='emphatic')
            li From here, you can add a delay before the effect starts, change the duration of the effect, and control whether or not the effect repeats.
            img(src="images/animation/opti.png")

         section.emphatic-text(data-bespoke-backdrop='emphatic')
            h2 Inserting Videos
  
         section.emphatic-text(data-bespoke-backdrop='emphatic')
            h3 To insert a video from a file:
            p 
               li From the Insert tab, click the Video drop-down arrow, then select Video on My PC.
            img(src="images/insert/i1.png")

         section.emphatic-text(data-bespoke-backdrop='emphatic')
            li Locate and select the desired video file, then click Insert.
            img(src="images/insert/i2.jpg")
   
         section.emphatic-text(data-bespoke-backdrop='emphatic')
            li The video will be added to the slide.
            img(src="images/insert/i3.jpg")
   
         section.emphatic-text(data-bespoke-backdrop='emphatic')
            h3 To insert an online video:
            p Some websites—like YouTube—allow you to embed videos into your slides. An embedded video will still be hosted on its original website, meaning the video itself won't be added to your file. Embedding can be a convenient way to reduce the file size of your presentation, but you'll also need to be connected to the Internet for the video to play.
            img(src=images/insert/i4.png")
   
         section.emphatic-text(data-bespoke-backdrop='emphatic')
             h3 To preview a video: 
             p 
               li Click a video to select it.
               li Click the Play/Pause button below the video. The video will begin playing, and the timeline next to the Play/Pause button will advance.
             img(src="images/insert/i5.png")

         section.emphatic-text(data-bespoke-backdrop='emphatic')
             li To jump to a different part of the video, click anywhere on the timeline.
             img(src="images/insert/i6.jpg")

         section.emphatic-text(data-bespoke-backdrop='emphatic')
             h3 Video options
             p There are other options you can set to control how your video will play. These are found in the Video Options group on the Playback tab.
 
         section.emphatic-text(data-bespoke-backdrop='emphatic')
             img(src="images/insert/i7.png")
             br 
             li Volume: Changes the audio volume for the video.
             li Start: Controls whether the video starts automatically or when the mouse is clicked.
             li Play Full Screen: Lets the video fill the entire screen while playing.
             li Hide While Not Playing: Hides the video when not playing.
             li Loop until Stopped: Replays the video until stopped.
             li Rewind after Playing: Returns the video to the beginning when it is finished playing.

      section.emphatic-text(data-bespoke-backdrop='emphatic')
        h3 To insert audio from a file:
        li From the Insert tab, click the Audio drop-down arrow, then select Audio on My PC.
        img(src="images/audio/audio1.png")

      section.emphatic-text(data-bespoke-backdrop='emphatic')
        li Locate and select the desired audio file, then click Insert.
        img(src="images/audio/audio2.png")
        li The audio file will be added to the slide.

      section.emphatic-text(data-bespoke-backdrop='emphatic')
        h2 Recording your own audio
        li Sometimes you may want to record audio directly into a presentation. For example, you might want the presentation to include narration. Before you begin, make sure you have a microphone that is compatible with your computer; many computers have built-in microphones or ones that can be plugged in to the computer.

